## Building a Modal Dialog in React

**Mental model:** A modal is conditionally-rendered overlay + content, plus three behaviours that make it *accessible*: close on Escape, close on backdrop click (but not content click), and lock background scroll while open. Keep it controlled — the parent owns `open`.

### Step 1 — Controlled open + structure
Render nothing when closed; otherwise a fixed backdrop wrapping a centered panel.

```jsx
if (!open) return null;
return (
  <div className="backdrop" onClick={onClose}>
    <div role="dialog" aria-modal="true" onClick={(e) => e.stopPropagation()}>{children}</div>
  </div>
);
```

### Step 2 — Backdrop vs content clicks
`stopPropagation` on the panel means only clicks on the backdrop itself close it.

### Step 3 — Close on Escape
Attach a `keydown` listener while open and remove it on cleanup.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  if (!open) return;
  const onKey = (e) => e.key === 'Escape' && onClose();
  window.addEventListener('keydown', onKey);
  return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', onKey);
}, [open, onClose]);
```

### Step 4 — Lock background scroll
Set `body` overflow while open and restore it on cleanup.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  if (!open) return;
  document.body.style.overflow = 'hidden';
  return () => { document.body.style.overflow = ''; };
}, [open]);
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Click drag from panel to backdrop | Use `onClick` (fires on same target) not `onMouseUp`. |
| Listener leaks | Every effect returns a cleanup. |
| Focus | Real apps trap focus and restore it to the trigger on close. |

**Interview tip:** Calling out the `stopPropagation` trick for "backdrop click closes, content click doesn't" is the detail interviewers wait for — and mention focus-trapping as the production next step even if you stub it.

