## Building a Modal Dialog in Angular

**Mental model:** A modal is an overlay shown with `*ngIf`, plus three accessibility behaviours: close on Escape, close on backdrop click (but not content click), and lock background scroll. Keep it controlled with an `open` input and a `close` output. Classic `NgModule` setup — no signals/standalone, and no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Input/output control
```typescript
@Input() open = false;
@Input() title = '';
@Output() closed = new EventEmitter<void>();
close(): void { this.closed.emit(); }
```

### Step 2 — Backdrop vs content clicks
Bind the backdrop click to `close()`, and stop propagation on the panel so inner clicks don't bubble.

```html
<div class="backdrop" (click)="close()">
  <div role="dialog" aria-modal="true" (click)="$event.stopPropagation()">...</div>
</div>
```

### Step 3 — Close on Escape
A `@HostListener` on `document:keydown.escape` fires only while the component exists.

```typescript
@HostListener('document:keydown.escape')
onEsc(): void { if (this.open) { this.close(); } }
```

### Step 4 — Lock background scroll
Toggle body overflow in `ngOnChanges`, and restore it in `ngOnDestroy`.

```typescript
ngOnChanges(): void { document.body.style.overflow = this.open ? 'hidden' : ''; }
ngOnDestroy(): void { document.body.style.overflow = ''; }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Content click closes | `$event.stopPropagation()` on the panel. |
| Escape key binding | `keydown.escape` is Angular's key-filter syntax. |
| Leak on destroy | `ngOnDestroy` restores body overflow. |

**Interview tip:** Angular's `(keydown.escape)` / `@HostListener('document:keydown.escape')` key-event filter syntax is worth naming — it's cleaner than reading `event.key` yourself and signals framework fluency.

